    # employees experience in string values has to be converted to a numerical one, as it plays a vital role

loan_data['emp_length_int'] = loan_data['emp_length'].str.replace("\+ years", "")

loan_data['emp_length_int'] = loan_data['emp_length_int'].str.replace("n/a", str(0))
loan_data['emp_length_int'] = loan_data['emp_length_int'].str.replace(" years", "")
loan_data['emp_length_int'] = loan_data['emp_length_int'].str.replace(" year", "")

    Data Preprocessing / Continuous / Earliest Credit Line¶

    This column gives us the time since the earliest credit was issued. The transformation is necessary because it's in the form or string and for evaluation we need to transform it into a timestamp.

    The very reason for converting it into timestamp is because we can then get the total time elapsed since the credit line was issued. In my view that will help us to get idea about how many of people paid in time, how many defaulted, how many prolonged, what profession of people were successful in paying the loan and which of them failed.

    By looking at the description, we can see that the minimum is negative. But how can the time difference be negative???

    The answer lies in the conversion of string to timestamp which we performed a bit earlier. While converting the time, the data that was dated before 1970 was evaluated as a century later. i.e. 2062 for 1962.

    The reason for it is that in any typical programming language, the time ranges from 1970-9999. Hence what we can do is to convert the negative difference to the maximum possible difference, as they date older than the max.

    We're separating good (non-defaulters) and bad (defaulters) from the dataset. How??

    By analyzing who have defaulted, charged off, or have a pending status for more than 90 days.

    The basic logic behind the code below is that say I have to categorize the credit and debit from my outlays as 1's and 0's. Then the numpy function np.where() comes to rescue.

    The whole thing can be read as WHEREVER IN THE COLUMN YOU FIND CREDIT THEN ASSIGN 1 OTHERWISE 0.

    In [337]:
    loan_data['good_bad'] = np.where(loan_data['loan_status'].isin(['Charged Off', 'Default', 'Late (31-120 days)']), 0, 1)

    Data Preprocessing / Splitting the data¶

    It's always a good practice to split the data into training set and test set. A ratio of 90:10 or 80:20 is generally preferred.

    Learn more about train-test_split

    Syntax: train_test_split(independent_var, dependent_var, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, shuffle=True)

    When there are many columns and only a few has to be taken out then pandas df.drop(columns, axis) helps us to escape that many columns. axis=0 means rows and axis=1 means columns

    So finally we can see that the value lies between 0.1-0.3 and hence grade as a whole has a medium predictive power.

    But let's automate the task. Shall we?

    In [458]:
    def calculate_woe(df, variable_for_iv, dependent_var):
    
    # concatenating the two columns  
    df = pd.concat([df[variable_for_iv], dependent_var], axis=1)    
    
    # since the first column(eg: grade) is categorical, it's a good thing to keep a count of default for each category.
    ''' I know that the target/output/y/default is in binary (1 for good(no_defualt) and 0 for default(bad), hence carrying out)
    the mean will give us a proportion of non default cases.'''
    
    df = pd.concat([df.groupby(df.columns.values[0], as_index = False)[df.columns.values[1]].count(),
                    df.groupby(df.columns.values[0], as_index = False)[df.columns.values[1]].mean()], axis=1)
    
    # since the groupby and concat causes repetation of grade, hence selecting only one of it.
    df = df.iloc[:, [0, 1, 3]]

    # renaming the column
    df.columns = [df.columns.values[0], 'n_obs', '%good_per_category']    
    
    # finding the percentage of defaulters for each category
    df['%bad_per_category'] = 1 - df['%good_per_category']    
    
    # finding the proportion of observation for each category
    df["prop_obs"] = df['n_obs'] / df['n_obs'].sum()    
    
    '''when I multiply **no_of_observation with the **proportion_of_good/bad, then we get the number of observation 
    of non-defaulters and defaulters.'''
    # say 100 obs for cat A, and 75% prop_good, then total good borrowers => 75% of 100 = 75
    df['n_good'] = df['n_obs'] * df['%good_per_category']
    df['n_bad'] = df['n_obs'] * df['%bad_per_category']
    
    # finding the percentage of non_defaulters and defaulters w.r.t all non_def and def.
    df['%good'] = df['n_good'] / df['n_good'].sum()
    df['%bad'] = df['n_bad'] / df['n_bad'].sum()
    
    # finding weight of evidence and sorting according to it.
    df['woe'] = np.log(df['%good'] / df['%bad'])
    df = df.sort_values(['woe'])
    df = df.reset_index(drop = True)
    
    # just knowing the difference of consequtive woe and prop_good
    df['diff_prop_good'] = df['%good'].diff().abs()
    df['diff_woe'] = df['woe'].diff().abs()
    
    # finally calculating information value.
    df['IV'] = ((df['%good'] - df['%bad']) * df['woe']).sum()
    
    return df

def lets_plot(df, rotation_of_x_axis_labels = 0): 
    x = np.array(df.iloc[:, 0].apply(str)) #np.array because matplotlib work better with numpy array.
    y = df['woe']
    plt.figure(figsize = (18,6))
    plt.plot(x, y, marker = "o", linestyle = "--", color = "k")
    plt.xlabel(df.columns[0])
    plt.ylabel('Weight of Evidence')
    plt.title(str("Weight of Evidence by " + df.columns[0]))
    plt.xticks(rotation = rotation_of_x_axis_labels)

    It's time that we create dummy variables for our discrete data. But didn't we do it before???

    Yes we have. But the main difference here is that, in our previous quest where we created dummy variables, we created dummies for each and every category whatsover. It was achieved using pd.get_dummies(df) function.

    What we are trying to do here is to calculate the woe and IV for individual variables and then grouping related categories that have relatively low woe.

    The main advantage that we get from it is that, number of categories will reduce and thus the dummy variable too. It greatly helps in minimizing the margin of error and increase the efficiency.

    Data Preprocessing / Continuous / Finetuning and Coarse Classing¶

    The difference between discrete and continuous w.r.t calculating woe is that, in discrete the order of the category doesnot matter. But in continuous, the order does matters and hence we won't sort the table of calculation w.r.t woe.

    In [477]:
    def calculate_woe_continuous(df, variable_for_iv, dependent_var):
    
    # concatenating the two columns  
    df = pd.concat([df[variable_for_iv], dependent_var], axis=1)    
    
    # since the first column(eg: grade) is categorical, it's a good thing to keep a count of default for each category.
    ''' I know that the target/output/y/default is in binary (1 for good(no_defualt) and 0 for default(bad), hence carrying out)
    the mean will give us a proportion of non default cases.'''
    
    df = pd.concat([df.groupby(df.columns.values[0], as_index = False)[df.columns.values[1]].count(),
                    df.groupby(df.columns.values[0], as_index = False)[df.columns.values[1]].mean()], axis=1)
    
    # since the groupby and concat causes repetation of grade, hence selecting only one of it.
    df = df.iloc[:, [0, 1, 3]]

    # renaming the column
    df.columns = [df.columns.values[0], 'n_obs', '%good_per_category']    
    
    # finding the percentage of defaulters for each category
    df['%bad_per_category'] = 1 - df['%good_per_category']    
    
    # finding the proportion of observation for each category
    df["prop_obs"] = df['n_obs'] / df['n_obs'].sum()    
    
    '''when I multiply **no_of_observation with the **proportion_of_good/bad, then we get the number of observation 
    of non-defaulters and defaulters.'''
    # say 100 obs for cat A, and 75% prop_good, then total good borrowers => 75% of 100 = 75
    df['n_good'] = df['n_obs'] * df['%good_per_category']
    df['n_bad'] = df['n_obs'] * df['%bad_per_category']
    
    # finding the percentage of non_defaulters and defaulters w.r.t all non_def and def.
    df['%good'] = df['n_good'] / df['n_good'].sum()
    df['%bad'] = df['n_bad'] / df['n_bad'].sum()
    
    # finding weight of evidence and sorting according to it.
    df['woe'] = np.log(df['%good'] / df['%bad'])
#     df = df.sort_values(['woe'])
#     df = df.reset_index(drop = True)
    
    # just knowing the difference of consequtive woe and prop_good
    df['diff_prop_good'] = df['%good'].diff().abs()
    df['diff_woe'] = df['woe'].diff().abs()
    
    # finally calculating information value.
    df['IV'] = ((df['%good'] - df['%bad']) * df['woe']).sum()
    
    return df

loan_data_inputs_prep['dti:>40']   = np.where((loan_data_inputs_prep['dti'] > 40), 1, 0)
